'''Philosopheme''' 

Webster Dictionary, 1913

phi*los"o*pheme (n.) [Gr., from to love knowledge]
A philosophical preposition, doctrine, or principal of reasoning. [R]

This, the most venerable, and perhaps the most ancient, of Grecian myths, is a philosopheme. ''Coleridge''

A philosopheme is a concept that translates from one language (in this case Greek)through every other language back into its self. 

